Kafka is a distributed Streaming platform. It does only three things

1. Publish and Subscribe to streams of records, similar to message queue or enterprise messaging system.
2. Store streams of records in a fault-tolerant durable way.
3. Process streams of records as they occur.

Message Location in Kafka:
Topic + Partition + Offset (TPO = X.2.1)

A partition is a commit log, It is an
Ordered, Immutable sequence of records.

A Kubernetes Pod

  1. A Pod is the basic building block of Kubernetes - the smallest and simplest unit in the Kubernetes Object model that is created or deployed. 
  2. It represents a single instance of an application in Kubernetes, which might consist of either a single container or a small number of containers that are tightly coupled and that shares resources (Network IP/Port, Storage, CPU and RAM.)
  3. A Pod represents a 'running process' on a cluster.
  4. Pods operate at one level higher than individual containers because it's very common to have a group of containers work together to produce an artifact or process a set of work.
  5. An example of a pod is an app server pod that contains three separate containers: the app server itself, a monitoring adapter, and a logging adapter. The logging and monitoring containers could be shared across all projects in your organization. These adapters could provide an abstraction between different cloud monitoring vendors or other destinations.
  6. Pods are used as the unit of replication in Kubernetes. If an application becomes too popular and a single pod instance can’t carry the load, Kubernetes can be configured to deploy new replicas of that pod to the cluster as necessary.

A Node

  1. is the smallest unit of computing hardware in Kubernetes. 
  2. It is a representation of a single machine in a cluster. In most production systems, a node will likely be either a physical machine in a datacenter, or virtual machine hosted on a cloud provider

Persistent Volumes

provide a file system that can be mounted to the cluster, without being associated with any particular node.

Docker Container

  1. A Docker container image is a lightweight, standalone, executable package of software that includes everything needed to run an application: code, runtime, system tools, system libraries and settings.
  2. Container images become containers at runtime and in the case of Docker containers - images become containers when they run on Docker Engine.

Deployment

  1. A deployment’s primary purpose is to declare how many replicas of a pod should be running at a time. 
  2. When a deployment is added to the cluster, it will automatically spin up the requested number of pods, and then monitor them. 
  3. If a pod dies, the deployment will automatically re-create it.

A replica is how Kubernetes accomplishes scaling out a deployment. A replica is a copy of a pod that already contains a running service. By having multiple replicas of a pod, you can ensure your deployment has the available resources to handle increasing load on your app.
